            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-12-10T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-12-10T12:00:00-05:00" n="586" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d586">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 P.W./12–1045: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-12-10T12:00:00-05:00">December 10, 1945—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2482. Point 5 of our proposals—namely the disarming of Japanese troops in North
                    China—was not directed to the Manchuria situation which is covered by Point 6.
                    In North China, excluding Manchuria, according to our information there are more
                    than 300,000 Japanese troops which have not been evacuated and only a little
                    more than half of them have been disarmed. Their disarmament and evacuation have
                    been delayed and complicated by civil strife. We simply want to advise Molotov
                    of the status of affairs and of the reasons why we have not been able to remove
                    our troops.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Byrnes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
